{"title_page": "Planet of the Humans", "text_new": "'''''Planet of the Humans''''' is an [[environmental]] [[documentary]] film that was directed by Jeff Gibbs and was released in 2019. It was backed and promoted by [[Michael Moore]].<ref>[https://www.apnews.com/933b49681b0d47d3a005d356f35251ab New Michael Moore-backed doc tackles alternative energy], Associated Press, August 8, 2019</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe film received it's world premiere at the [[Traverse City Film Festival]] in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.record-eagle.com/news/go/planet-of-the-humans-local-mans-documentary-debuts-at-film-festival/article_3d05803a-a8f6-11e9-9ae1-737ecef2af30.html|title='Planet of the Humans': Local man's documentary debuts at film festival|last=smcwhirter@record-eagle.com|first=Sheri Mcwhirter|website=Traverse City Record-Eagle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> On April 21, 2020, the eve of [[Earth Day]], Moore announced that the film would be available for free on YouTube for 30 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/michael-moore-releases-planet-of-the-humans-documentary-eve-earth-day-1202913761/|title=Michael Moore Releases \u2018Planet Of The Humans\u2019 Documentary For Free On Eve Of Earth Day|last=Petski|first=Denise|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|date=2020-04-21|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n[[Peter Bradshaw]] in the Guardian called the film \"refereshingly contrarian.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/apr/22/planet-of-the-humans-review-environment-michael-moore-jeff-gibbs|title=Planet of the Humans review \u2013 contrarian eco-doc from the Michael Moore stable|date=2020-04-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Gary Mason (journalist)|Gary Mason]] in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' referred to the film as, \"The Michael Moore-backed film enviros are dreading.\"<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-the-michael-moore-backed-film-enviros-are-dreading/ The Michael Moore-backed film enviros are dreading], Globe and Mail, August 23, 2019</ref>\n\nThe [[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] wrote of the movie, \"Mr. Gibbs and Mr. Moore critique wind energy for requiring enormous amounts of copper and rare earth minerals. Wind farms also require developing large tracts of land. Solar energy gets dinged for its dependence on mining coal and quartz.\"<ref>[https://www.reviewjournal.com/opinion/editorials/editorial-michael-moore-backed-film-criticizes-renewable-energy-1829377/ Michael Moore-backed film criticizes renewable energy], Las Vegas Review-Journal, August 18, 2019</ref>\n\n[[Denis Harvey|Dennis Harvey]] in [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]  claims \"Gibbs\u2019 dull monotone makes him a poor narrator\", \"there\u2019s nothing particularly elegant about the way \u201cPlanet of the Humans\u201d arrives at its downbeat thesis,\" and \"though well-shot and edited, the material here is simply too sprawling to avoid feeling crammed into one ungainly package.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/reviews/planet-of-the-humans-film-review-1234586660/|title=\u2018Planet of the Humans\u2019: Film Review|last=Harvey|first=Dennis|last2=Harvey|first2=Dennis|date=2020-04-22|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|4pXCftKF4uI|Planet of the Humans - Teaser Trailer}}\n*{{youtube|Zk11vI-7czE|Michael Moore Presents: Planet of the Humans {{pipe}} Full Documentary {{pipe}} Directed by Jeff Gibbs}}\n*[https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/planet_of_the_humans Planet of the Humans] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Climate change films]]\n[[Category:Michael Moore]]\n[[Category:Renewable energy]]\n[[Category:Human overpopulation]]\n[[Category:Alternative energy]]\n[[Category:Fossil fuels]]\n\n\n{{documentary-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''''Planet of the Humans''''' is an [[environmental]] [[documentary]] film that was directed by Jeff Gibbs and was released in 2019. It was backed and promoted by [[Michael Moore]].<ref>[https://www.apnews.com/933b49681b0d47d3a005d356f35251ab New Michael Moore-backed doc tackles alternative energy], Associated Press, August 8, 2019</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe film received it's world premiere at the [[Traverse City Film Festival]] in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.record-eagle.com/news/go/planet-of-the-humans-local-mans-documentary-debuts-at-film-festival/article_3d05803a-a8f6-11e9-9ae1-737ecef2af30.html|title='Planet of the Humans': Local man's documentary debuts at film festival|last=smcwhirter@record-eagle.com|first=Sheri Mcwhirter|website=Traverse City Record-Eagle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> On April 21, 2020, the eve of [[Earth Day]], Moore announced that the film would be available for free on YouTube for 30 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/michael-moore-releases-planet-of-the-humans-documentary-eve-earth-day-1202913761/|title=Michael Moore Releases \u2018Planet Of The Humans\u2019 Documentary For Free On Eve Of Earth Day|last=Petski|first=Denise|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|date=2020-04-21|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n[[Peter Bradshaw]] in the Guardian called the film \"refereshingly contrarian.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/apr/22/planet-of-the-humans-review-environment-michael-moore-jeff-gibbs|title=Planet of the Humans review \u2013 contrarian eco-doc from the Michael Moore stable|date=2020-04-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Gary Mason (journalist)|Gary Mason]] in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' referred to the film as, \"The Michael Moore-backed film enviros are dreading.\"<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-the-michael-moore-backed-film-enviros-are-dreading/ The Michael Moore-backed film enviros are dreading], Globe and Mail, August 23, 2019</ref>\n\nThe [[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] wrote of the movie, \"Mr. Gibbs and Mr. Moore critique wind energy for requiring enormous amounts of copper and rare earth minerals. Wind farms also require developing large tracts of land. Solar energy gets dinged for its dependence on mining coal and quartz.\"<ref>[https://www.reviewjournal.com/opinion/editorials/editorial-michael-moore-backed-film-criticizes-renewable-energy-1829377/ Michael Moore-backed film criticizes renewable energy], Las Vegas Review-Journal, August 18, 2019</ref>\\\n\n[[Denis Harvey|Dennis Harvey]] in [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]  claims \"Gibbs\u2019 dull monotone makes him a poor narrator\", \"there\u2019s nothing particularly elegant about the way \u201cPlanet of the Humans\u201d arrives at its downbeat thesis,\" and \"though well-shot and edited, the material here is simply too sprawling to avoid feeling crammed into one ungainly package.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/reviews/planet-of-the-humans-film-review-1234586660/|title=\u2018Planet of the Humans\u2019: Film Review|last=Harvey|first=Dennis|last2=Harvey|first2=Dennis|date=2020-04-22|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|4pXCftKF4uI|Planet of the Humans - Teaser Trailer}}\n*{{youtube|Zk11vI-7czE|Michael Moore Presents: Planet of the Humans {{pipe}} Full Documentary {{pipe}} Directed by Jeff Gibbs}}\n*[https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/planet_of_the_humans Planet of the Humans] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Climate change films]]\n[[Category:Michael Moore]]\n[[Category:Renewable energy]]\n[[Category:Human overpopulation]]\n[[Category:Alternative energy]]\n[[Category:Fossil fuels]]\n\n\n{{documentary-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WayneMokane", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:remove spurious backslash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planet_of_the_Humans"}
{"title_page": "Kimiko Yo", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Kimiko Yo\n| native_name = \u4f59 \u8cb4\u7f8e\u5b50\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1956|5|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Yokohama]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture]], Japan\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| other_names = \n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1987 \u2013 present\n| spouse = \n| website = \n| awards = \n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Kimiko Yo'''|\u4f59 \u8cb4\u7f8e\u5b50|Yo Kimiko|born 12 May 1956}} is a Japanese actress. She was given Best Supporting Actress awards at the 2004 and the 2009 [[Yokohama Film Festival]] ceremonies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/Sections/Awards/Yokohama_Film_Festival/2004|accessdate=2009-04-16|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|title=Yokohama Film Festival: 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/Sections/Awards/Yokohama_Film_Festival/2009|accessdate=2009-04-16|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|title=Yokohama Film Festival: 2009}}</ref> She won the award for best supporting actress at the 32nd and at the 33rd [[Japan Academy Prize (film)|Japan Academy Prize]] for ''[[Departures (2008 film)|Departures]]'' and ''[[Dear Doctor (film)|Dear Doctor]]'' respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=32 |script-title=ja:\u7b2c 32 \u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1 |accessdate=2011-01-05 |language=Japanese |publisher=Japan Academy Prize |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714155924/http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=32 |archivedate=14 July 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.japan-academy-prize.jp/prizes/?t=33 |script-title=ja:\u7b2c 33 \u56de\u65e5\u672c\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc\u8cde\u512a\u79c0\u4f5c\u54c1|accessdate= 2011-01-05|language= Japanese|publisher= Japan Academy Prize}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nYo was born in [[Yokohama]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture]]. Her mother is Japanese and her father, who moved to Japan for business and later founded the Hakka Association in Japan, is [[Hakka people|Hakka]] [[Taiwan]]ese.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Films===\n*''[[Ch\u014dchin (film)|Ch\u014dchin]]'' (1987)\n*''[[A Sign Days]]'' (1989)\n*''[[Hiruko the Goblin]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Yumeji]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Evil Dead Trap 3: Broken Love Killer]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Ghost Pub]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Sharaku (film)|Sharaku]]'' (1995)\n*''[[School Ghost Stories]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Moonlight Serenade (1997 film)|Moonlight Serenade]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Wait and See (1998 film)|Wait and See]]'' (1998)\n*''[[Tsuribaka Nisshi Eleven]]'' (2000)\n*''[[New Battles Without Honor and Humanity (2000 film)|New Battles Without Honor and Humanity]]'' (2000)\n*''[[Suicide Club (film)|Suicide Club]]'' (2002)\n*''[[Aiki (film)|Aiki]]'' (2002)\n*''[[Caf\u00e9 Lumi\u00e8re]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Drugstore Girl]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Tokyo Tower (film)|Tokyo Tower]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Break Through!]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Yamato (film)|Yamato]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Virgin Snow (film)|Virgin Snow]]'' (2007)\n*''[[The Ramen Girl]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Departures (2008 film)|Departures]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Air Doll]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Dear Doctor (film)|Dear Doctor]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Villain (2010 film)|Villain]]'' (2010)\n*''[[The Lone Scalpel]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Rebirth (2011 film)|Rebirth]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Hoshi Mamoru Inu]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Tsure ga Utsu ni Narimashite]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Dirty Hearts]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Bread of Happiness]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Ace Attorney (film)|Ace Attorney]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Gaiji Keisatsu]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Ai to Makoto]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Anata e]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Shield of Straw]]'' (2013)\n*''[[A Story of Yonosuke]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Parasyte: Part 1]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Shinya Shokud\u014d]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Tsukuroi Tatsu Hito (film)|Tsukuroi Tatsu Hito]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Shin Godzilla]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Black Widow Business]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Midnight Diner