2015/01/06/ant-man-comic-book-exclusive-preview/21321837/|title='Ant-Man' looms large on Marvel's horizon|work=USA Today|date=January 6, 2015|accessdate=January 2, 2017}}\n*{{cite web|ref={{SfnRef|\"Ultimate Spider-Man: Web Warriors\"|n.d.}}|url=http://www.locatetv.com/tv/ultimate-spider-man/season-3/9103833|title=Ultimate Spider-Man: Web Warriors Season 3 Episode 16|work=Locate TV|accessdate=March 24, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326074126/http://www.locatetv.com/tv/ultimate-spider-man/season-3/9103833|archivedate=March 26, 2015}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.marvel.com/universe/Ant-Man_%28Scott_Lang%29 Ant-Man (Scott Lang)] at Marvel.com\n* [http://www.marveldirectory.com/individuals/a/antmanii.htm Marvel Directory: Ant Man II]\n\n{{Hank Pym}}\n{{Fantastic Four}}\n{{Avengers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ant-Man}}\n[[Category:American superheroes]]\n[[Category:Ant-Man]]\n[[Category:Avengers (comics) characters]]\n[[Category:Characters created by David Michelinie]]\n[[Category:Characters created by John Byrne]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1979]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Florida]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who can change size]]\n[[Category:Fictional electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:Fictional professional thieves]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Male characters in film]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics superheroes]]\n[[Category:Superhero film characters]]\n", "name_user": "Favre1fan93", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ant-Man_(Scott_Lang)"}
{"title_page": "White House Down", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 American film by Roland Emmerich}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = White House Down\n| image          = White House Down poster with billing block.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Roland Emmerich]]\n| producer       = Roland Emmerich<br />[[Channing Tatum]]<br />[[Bradley J. Fischer (producer)|Bradley J. Fischer]]<br />[[Harald Kloser]]<br />[[James Vanderbilt]]<br />[[Larry Franco]]<br />[[Laeta Kalogridis]]\n| writer         = James Vanderbilt\n| starring       = Channing Tatum<br />[[Jamie Foxx]]<br />[[Maggie Gyllenhaal]]<br />[[Joey King]]<br />[[Jason Clarke]]<br />[[Richard Jenkins]]<br />[[James Woods]]<!-- Do not add Joey King on here since she isn't listed in the theatrical poster -->\n| music          = Harald Kloser<br />[[Thomas Wanker|Thomas Wander]]\n| cinematography = [[Anna Foerster]]\n| editing        = Adam Wolfe\n| studio         = [[Columbia Pictures]]<br />[[Centropolis Entertainment]]<br />[[James Vanderbilt|Mythology Entertainment]]\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Motion Picture Group#Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures Releasing]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|06|28|United States}}<!--- per [[WP:FILMRELEASE]] --->\n| runtime        = 131 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 131:29--><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/white-house-down-2013-3 |title=''WHITE HOUSE DOWN'' (12A) |work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $150 million<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=whitehousedown.htm |title=White House Down (2013) |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=October 2, 2013}}</ref>\n| gross          = $205.4 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n| image_size     =\n| border         =\n}}\n'''''White House Down''''' is a 2013 American [[Political thriller|political]] [[action film|action]] [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] film directed and co-produced by [[Roland Emmerich]], written by [[James Vanderbilt]] and produced by Vanderbilt, [[Bradley J. Fischer]], [[Harald Kloser]], [[Larry Franco]] and [[Laeta Kalogridis]]. In the film, a divorced US Capitol Police officer named John Cale attempts rescuing both his daughter Emily and the President of the United States James Sawyer when a massively destructive terrorist assault occurs in the [[White House]]. The film stars [[Channing Tatum]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Maggie Gyllenhaal]], [[Joey King]], [[Jason Clarke]], [[Richard Jenkins]], and [[James Woods]].\n\nReleased on June 28, 2013 by [[Sony Pictures Releasing|Sony Pictures]], ''White House Down'' received mixed reviews from critics toward the screenwriting and the cliched storyline, although the performances and action sequences were praised. The film  grossed over $205 million worldwide against budget of $150 million.<ref name=\"mojo\"/> ''White House Down'' was one of two films released in 2013 that dealt with a terrorist attack on the White House; the other was ''[[Olympus Has Fallen]]'', released three months earlier.\n\n==Plot==\n[[President of the United States|U.S. President]] James Sawyer ([[Jamie Foxx]]) makes a controversial proposal to remove military forces from the [[Middle East]]. Divorced [[United States Capitol Police|Capitol Police]] officer John Cale ([[Channing Tatum]]) is assigned to [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] Eli Raphelson ([[Richard Jenkins]]), whose nephew he saved while serving in [[Afghanistan]]. Cale hopes to impress his daughter Emily ([[Joey King]]) by interviewing for the [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] Presidential Detail, getting tickets for them to tour the White House. His interviewer, Deputy [[Special Agent]]-in-Charge Carol Finnerty ([[Maggie Gyllenhaal]]), a college acquaintance, deems him unqualified for the job.\n\nA bomb is detonated in the [[United States Capitol]], sending the White House into lockdown. Finnerty escorts Raphelson to an underground command center in [[the Pentagon]], while [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] Alvin Hammond ([[Michael Murphy (actor)|Michael Murphy]]) is taken aboard [[Air Force One]]. A team of mercenaries led by ex-[[Delta Force]] commando Emil Stenz ([[Jason Clarke (actor)|Jason Clarke]]) infiltrate the White House disguised as video technicians and overwhelm the Secret Service, taking the tour group hostage in the [[Blue Room (White House)|Blue Room]] and seizing the building. Cale escapes to find Emily, separated during the tour. Retiring Head of the Presidential Detail [[Special Agent]]-in-Charge Martin Walker ([[James Woods]]) brings Sawyer to the [[Presidential Emergency Operations Center|PEOC]] beneath the [[Library (White House)|Library]]. Inside, Walker kills Sawyer's detail, revealing himself as the leader of the attack, apparently seeking vengeance against Sawyer for a botched black ops mission in [[Iran]] the year prior that resulted in the death of Walker's son. Cale kills a mercenary, taking his weapon and radio, and rescues Sawyer after overhearing Walker's plans.\n\nWalker brings in ex-[[National Security Agency|NSA]] analyst Skip Tyler ([[Jimmi Simpson]]) to hack the defense system, but requires Sawyer to activate the [[nuclear football]]. Right-wing sociopath Carl Killick ([[Kevin Rankin (actor)|Kevin Rankin]]) catches Emily filming the intruders on her phone and takes her hostage. Cale and Sawyer contact the command structure, using Emily's [[YouTube]] video to discover the mercenaries all formerly worked for government agencies. Cale and Sawyer try to escape via a secret tunnel but find the exit rigged with explosives. They escape in the presidential limo but are attacked by Stenz and fall into the White House pool. With Sawyer and Cale presumed dead in an explosion, the [[Twenty-fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] is invoked; Hammond is sworn in as president. Cale and Sawyer, still alive, learn Hammond has ordered an aerial incursion to re-acquire the White House, but the mercenaries shoot down the helicopters. Learning Emily's identity from the video, Stenz takes her to Walker in the [[Oval Office]]. Hacking into [[North American Aerospace Defense Command|NORAD]], Tyler launches a missile at Air Force One from [[Piketon, Ohio]], killing Hammond and everyone on board. Raphelson is sworn in as president and orders an air strike on the White House.\n\nSawyer surrenders himself to save Emily. Walker, blaming Iran for his son's death, demands Sawyer use the football to launch nuclear missiles against various Iranian cities. Sawyer refuses, while Cale sets fire to several rooms as a diversion. Tyler inadvertently triggers the tunnel explosives and is vaporized. Killing most of the mercenaries and freeing the hostages, Cale blows Stenz up with a grenade belt. Sawyer attacks Walker, who uses Sawyer's handprint to activate the football and target the Iranian cities, when Cale crashes a reinforced [[Chevrolet Suburban]] through the Oval Office. Before Walker can launch the missiles, Cale kills him with the car's [[rotary cannon]]. Emily waves off the incoming fighter planes with a presidential flag, calling off the air strike.\n\nCale realizes that Raphelson was Walker's accomplice. Believing Sawyer dead and that Cale has no proof, Raphelson is tricked into confessing and is arrested for [[treason]]. Sawyer names Cale his new special agent, taking him and Emily on an aerial tour of DC. Sawyer receives word that [[France]], [[Russia]], [[Israel]] and Iran have agreed to his peace deal after learning of events at the White House, calling for an end to all wars.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Channing Tatum]] as John Cale, a [[United States Capitol Police]] officer.<ref name=\"tatum\">{{cite journal | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/channing-tatum-white-house-down-324079 | title=Channing Tatum in Talks to Star in 'White House Down' | journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=May 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Jamie Foxx]] as James Sawyer, the [[President of the United States]].<ref name=\"foxx\">{{cite journal | last1=Sneider | first1=Jeff | last2=Kroll | first2=Justin | url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118055125?refCatId=13 | title=Foxx nominated for 'White House Down' | journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=June 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Maggie Gyllenhaal]] as Carol Finnerty, Secret Service Presidential Detail Deputy Special Agent-in-Charge.<ref name=\"gyllenhaal\">{{cite journal | last1=Sneider | first1=Jeff | last2=Kroll | first2=Justin | url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118055170 | title=Maggie Gyllenhaal joins 'White House' staff | journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=June 7, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Jason Clarke]] as Emil Stenz, an ex-[[Delta Force]] commando and [[CIA]] operative who leads a group of mercenaries in infiltrating and taking over the White House.<ref>{{cite news | last=Patten | first=Dominic | url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/08/roland-emmerich-white-house-down-jason-clarke-roland-emmerich-channing-tatum-jamie-foxx-movie-casting/ | title=Roland Emmerich's 'White House Down' Adds Jason Clarke To Cast | website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=August 2, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Richard Jenkins]] as Eli Raphelson, [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"jenkins\">{{cite journal | last1=Sneider | first1=Jeff | last2=Kroll | first2=Justin | url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118056625 | title=Richard Jenkins joins 'White House Down' | journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=July 16, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Joey King]] as Emily Cale, the daughter of John Cale.<ref name=\"king\">{{cite journal | last=Sneider | first=Jeff | url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118057015?refcatid=13 | title=Joey King 'Down' to play Tatum's daughter | journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=July 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[James Woods]] as Martin James Walker, Head of the Secret Service Presidential Detail Special Agent-in-Charge.<ref name=\"woods\">{{cite journal | last=Kroll | first=Justin | url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118056355?refCatId=13 | title=James Woods in talks for 'White House Down' | journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=July 9, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Nicolas Wright]] as Donnie Donaldson, White House Tour Guide.\n* [[Jimmi Simpson]] as Skip Tyler, an ex-[[National Security Agency|NSA]] computer hacker and the technical specialist in Stenz's group.\n* [[Michael Murphy (actor)|Michael Murphy]] as Alvin Hammond, the [[Vice President of the United States]].<ref name=\"murphy\">{{cite news |last=Patten |first=Dominic |url= https://www.deadline.com/2012/08/white-house-down-adds-michael-murphy-vice-president-channing-tatum-jamie-foxx-maggie-gyllenhaal/ |title=\"White House Down\" Adds Michael Murphy |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 9, 2012 |accessdate=October 3, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Rachelle Lefevre]] as Melanie Cale, the former wife of John Cale and the mother of Emily Cale.<ref name=\"lefevre\">{{cite journal | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/twilight-rachel-lefevre-white-house-down-homefront-373640 | title=Twilight Actress Joins 'White House Down,' 'Homefront' | journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=September 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Lance Reddick]] as General Caulfield, [[Vice Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]].<ref name=\"reddick\">{{cite journal | last=Sneider | first=Jeff | url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118057459 | title='White House Down' elects Lance Reddick | journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=August 3, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Matt Craven]] as Roy Kellerman, Capitol Police officer.\n* [[Jake Weber]] as Ted Hope, Secret Service agent.\n* [[Peter Jacobson]] as Wallace, Vice President Chief of Staff.\n* [[Barbara Williams (actress)|Barbara Williams]] as Muriel Walker, Martin Walker's wife.\n* [[Kevin Rankin (actor)|Kevin Rankin]] as Carl Killick, a [[sociopathy|sociopathic]] [[white supremacy|white supremacist]] and one of Stenz's henchmen.\n* [[Garcelle Beauvais]] as Alison Sawyer, [[First Lady of the United States]].<ref name=\"beauvais\">{{cite journal | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/garcelle-beauvais-white-house-down-jamie-foxx-360935 | title=Garcelle Beauvais Joins 'White House Down' | journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=August 10, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Falk Hentschel]] as Motts, one of Stenz's henchmen.\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n''White House Down'' is directed by [[Roland Emmerich]] and based on a screenplay by [[James Vanderbilt]], who is also one of the film's producers. Sony Pictures purchased Vanderbilt's [[spec script]] in March 2012 for {{nowrap|$3 million}}, in what ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' called \"one of the biggest spec sales in quite a while\". The journal said the script was similar \"tonally and thematically\" to the films ''[[Die Hard]]'' and ''[[Air Force One (film)|Air Force One]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/sony-3-million-james-vanderbilt-306192 | title=Sony Plunking Down $3 Million for 'White House Down' by James Vanderbilt | journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=March 30, 2012 }}</ref> In the following April, Sony hired [[Roland Emmerich]] as director.<ref>{{cite news | last=Fleming | first=Mike | url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/04/roland-emmerich-in-talks-to-helm-3-million-sony-spec-white-house-down/ | title=Roland Emmerich in Talks to Helm $3 Million Sony Spec 'White House Down' | website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=April 2, 2012 }}</ref> Emmerich began filming in July 2012 at the La Cit\u00e9 Du Cin\u00e9ma in [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec, Canada]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Kelly | first=Brendan | url=http://blogs.montrealgazette.com/2012/07/17/channing-tatum-jamie-foxx-maggie-gyllenhaal-and-james-woods-coming-to-town-to-shoot-white-house-down/ | title=Channing Tatum, Jamie Foxx, Maggie Gyllenhaal, and James Woods coming to town to shoot White House Down | work=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]] | location=Montreal | date=July 17, 2012 }}</ref> Cinematographer [[Anna Foerster]] shot the film with [[Arri Alexa]] [[Arri Alexa#Alexa Plus|Plus]] [[digital cinematography|digital cameras]].<ref name=\"ac\">{{cite journal | author=Goldman, Michael | title=Prime Target | journal=[[American Cinematographer]] | publisher=[[American Society of Cinematographers]] | volume=94 | issue=7 | page=34 | location=[[Los Angeles, California]], United States | date=July 1, 2013 | issn=0002-7928 <!-- |accessdate=August 8, 2013 -->}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Sony competed with [[Millennium Films]], who were producing ''[[Olympus Has Fallen]]'' ([[twin films|also about]] a takeover of the White House) to complete casting and to begin filming.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/antoine-fuqua-olympus-gerard-butler-310176 | title=Antoine Fuqua Circling 'Olympus' as White House Thriller Race Heats Up | journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=April 10, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''White House Down'' was originally scheduled for a November 1, 2013<ref name=\"moving\">{{cite journal | last=McClintock | first=Pamela | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sony-white-house-down-channing-tatum-358648 | title=Sony Moving 'White House Down' to Heart of Summer 2013 | journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=August 6, 2012 }}</ref> release, but was moved up to a June 28, 2013 release.\n\nThe film was released on DVD and Blu-ray Disc on November 5, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/White-House-Down-Hit-Blu-ray-DVD-November-39277.html|title=White House Down Will Hit Blu-ray And DVD In November|publisher=cinemablend|last=Rawden|first=Jessica|date=September 3, 2013|accessdate=September 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n''White House Down'' received mixed reviews from critics. [[Review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a rating of 50%, based on 191 reviews, with a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 5.4/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''White House Down'' benefits from the leads' chemistry, but director Roland Emmerich smothers the film with narrative clich\u00e9s and choppily edited action.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/white_house_down/ |title=White House Down (2013) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted average score to reviews, the film has an average score of 52 out of 100, based on 43 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/white-house-down |title=White House Down Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRoth Cornet of [[IGN]] gives it a 6.5/10, concluding: \"''White House Down'' is a pretty silly rehashing of previously tread action movie territory, but if you're willing to laugh along with (or even at) it, it can be a highly entertaining experience.\"<ref>{{cite web | author = Roth Cornet |url= https://ign.com/articles/2013/06/26/white-house-down-review/ |publisher= [[Ziff Davis|Ziff Davis Media]] | work = [[IGN]] |title= ''White House Down''|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAndrew Chan of the [[Film Critics Circle of Australia]] writes, \"I am not entirely sure, whether I should be happy or sad that I laughed when someone got shot or bombed, but such is the manner of how the film is played out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehkneo.com/blog/?p=4222|title=White House Down|date=29 August 2013|author=Andrew Chan|publisher=[HK Neo Reviews]}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n===Box office===\nThe film grossed $73.1 million in the United States and $132.3 million internationally for a total gross of $205.4 million, against a budget of $150 million.<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=2334879|title=White House Down}}\n* {{mojo title|whitehousedown|White House Down}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|white_house_down|White House Down}}\n* {{metacritic film|id=white-house-down|title=White House Down}}\n* {{Amg movie|564886}} by Jason Buchanan\n\n{{Roland Emmerich}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White House Down}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American buddy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American political thriller films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about fictional Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:United States presidential succession in fiction]]\n[[Category:World War III speculative fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about Delta Force]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roland Emmerich]]\n[[Category:Films produced by James Vanderbilt]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Harald Kloser]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2014]]\n[[Category:Films set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Films set in the White House]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by James Vanderbilt]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013 American film by Roland Emmerich}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = White House Down\n| image          = White House Down poster with billing block.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Roland Emmerich]]\n| producer       = Roland Emmerich<br />[[Channing Tatum]]<br />[[Bradley J. Fischer (producer)|Bradley J.